04211nam a22006735i 9780804794268DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047942687 a10.1515/97808047942682doi  a(DE-B1597)563765  a(OCoLC)1198929814  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS481.A6bK86 2016 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a954.0352231 aKumar, Aishwary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRadical Equality :bAmbedkar, Gandhi, and the Risk of Democracy /cAishwary Kumar. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Memory in the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Of Faith in Equality -- t2 Spirits of Satyagraha -- t3 Laws of Force -- t4 Apotheosis of the Unequal -- t5 The Freedom of Others -- t6 Gandhi, the Reader -- t7 Responding Justly -- tEpilogue -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aB.R. Ambedkar, the architect of India's constitution, and M.K. Gandhi, the Indian nationalist, two figures whose thought and legacies have most strongly shaped the contours of Indian democracy, are typically considered antagonists who held irreconcilable views on empire, politics, and society. As such, they are rarely studied together. This book reassesses their complex relationship, focusing on their shared commitment to equality and justice, which for them was inseparable from anticolonial struggles for sovereignty. Both men inherited the concept of equality from Western humanism, but their ideas mark a radical turn in humanist conceptions of politics. This study recovers the philosophical foundations of their thought in Indian and Western traditions, religious and secular alike. Attending to moments of difficulty in their conceptions of justice and their languages of nonviolence, it probes the nature of risk that radical democracy's desire for inclusion opens within modern political thought. In excavating Ambedkar and Gandhi's intellectual kinship, Radical Equality allows them to shed light on each other, even as it places them within a global constellation of moral and political visions. The story of their struggle against inequality, violence, and empire thus transcends national boundaries and unfolds within a universal history of citizenship and dissent.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAnti-imperialist movementszIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aDemocracyzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aEqualityzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNonviolencezIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmbedkar. 4aDalit. 4aGandhi. 4acaste. 4aforce. 4ajustice. 4aminority. 4areligion. 4aresistance. 4asovereignty. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804794268zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804794268423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804794268.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles